Project Summary : Histological Cancer Detection Kaggle Mini-Project¶

Project Steps:¶

  1. Problem and Data Description
  2. Exploratory Data Analysis and Data Preperation
  3. Initial Model Architecture
  4. Analysis of Results
  5. Alternate Architecture and Hyper Parameter Tuning
  6. Conslusions

1. Problem and Data Description¶

Problem Overview:¶

Visual inspection of potentially cancerous cells is a time consuming and technical process that can have incredibly deleterious effects if incorrect. By leveraging the process of Computer vision and convolutional nueral networks (CNN) a sufficiently accurate system can be devised to help reduce workload on medical professionals. Alternatively the CNN could serve as the first step in a premptive screening process, to help early detection, without having to wait for a doctor to review the images.

Data Description¶

The dataset we will be training and testing on is composed of "" images with corresponding labels of non-malignant (0) and malignant (1) cell clusters. Each of the pictures we will be using is a (96 pixel x 96 pixel) image in a .tif format. The data is divided into a train and test set already, but for the purposes of this notebook being self contained, we will further split the trian set into a train and validation set.

Since this is close to a 50-50 split we wont have to further curtail the dataset to give the learning algorithm a better chance of accurately identifying malignancy.

def fp(direc, file):
    return f"{direc}{file}"

Creating a transformer for our data¶

The transformer will be responsible from converting our images into the array like structures (tensors) that our Convolutional nueral network will operate on.

In [8]:
# For the first round of architecture we will try a 96x96 transformation (the original size of the picture)
# For future architectures we will consider additional transforms including but not limited to horizontal and vertical
# reflection and rotations of images.

data_transformer = transforms.Compose([transforms.Resize((96, 96)), 
                                       transforms.ToTensor(), 
                                       transforms.Normalize(mean=(0.5, 0.5, 0.5), std=(0.5, 0.5, 0.5))])

Use of Data Storage Class and Data Loaders¶

I struggled for a bit wondering how best to store the data and give it to the CNN as we move forward with the project. While looking for solutions I came across two kaggle notebooks that used similar solutions to the problem. They both designed a class to store the data and then implemented a DataLoader. So for transparency's sake I've included a link to both notebooks below, and I have left the earlier attempt unedited above. This will mean there is some overlap in what we're accomplishing.

  1. https://www.kaggle.com/code/shtrausslearning/pytorch-cnn-binary-image-classification/notebook#1
  2. https://www.kaggle.com/code/oknashar/histopathologic-cancer-detection-using-pytorch

Finally the documentation on Data storage and Loading proved extremely useful: https://pytorch.org/tutorials/beginner/basics/data_tutorial.html

In [123]:
# Data Storage Class
#We need the class to accomplish 3 things, initialize based on set of data it is given, return length of given data, and 
#provide a method for getting the items.
#We will use the pytorch Dataset class as a parent class

class data_storage(Dataset):
    
    def __init__(self, directory, transformation):
        '''
            Initialize the data storage object by retriving file_handles and constructing
            label data frame
            
            params:
                directory - Full directory path where the files of interest are to be found
                transformation - The transformation we wish to apply to all of the files (at a 
                minimum this must include .To_Vector())
                
            returns:
                None
        '''
        #Create list of files
        file_names = os.listdir(directory)
        
        #Reduced data set for setting up the CNN
        self.files = [os.path.join(directory, file_name) for file_name in os.listdir(directory)]
#        self.files = [os.path.join(directory, file_name) for file_name in os.listdir(directory)]
        
        #Get labels from csv file
        if 'test' not in directory:
            label_df = pd.read_csv("histopathologic-cancer-detection\\train_labels.csv", index_col = 'id')
        else:
            label_df = pd.read_csv("histopathologic-cancer-detection\\sample_submission.csv", index_col = 'id')
        
        #Get the case name without the .tif ending from the filehandles to be used for indexing label_df
        self.case_id = [file_handle[:-4] for file_handle in file_names]
        
        #Create a list of labels that will match the order of cases in self.files
        self.labels = [label_df.loc[id_value].values[0] for id_value in self.case_id]
        
        #Store the transformation passed to the storage object, this will make it easier to make
        #adjustments to the feature modifications during hyperparameter tuning
        
        self.transformation = transformation

    def __getitem__(self, index):
        
        '''
            Returns transformed image and label at index location
            
            params:
                index - Numeric index of file to open
            
            returns:
                Transformed Image, Label
        '''
        
        #This will return a CNN ready object, meaning it needs to open the image with PIL Image.open() method,
        #transform the image with the given transform, and return image AND label.
        
        return self.transformation(Image.open(self.files[index])), self.labels[index]
        
    def __len__(self):
        
        '''
            Returns the number of files stored in the object
            
            params:
            
            returns:
                Number of files in object
            
        '''
        
        #gives the number of files in the object
        return len(self.files)

3. Initial Model Architecture¶

For our model we are going to use a basic unit of Convolution -> Convolution -> MaxPool. For the initial architecture we are going to have one unit of this pattern, with both Convolutions using a 3x3 frame. We will use 2 fully connected layers for our output. This framework was chosen as the base to work off of, and I assume that some tweaking in the Alternate architecture section of the notebook will yield better results. However there are some justifications for what we are choosing here, the 3x3 frame for the convolutions is chosen to minimize computational intesity while preserving information. Since we aren't padding (yet) I didn't want to include a larger 5x5 or 7x7 frame. The maxpool (2,2) step after 2 convolutions will help to keep dimensions low for the final fully connected stage. This is important because while the local machine hosting the notebook is GPU capable, long run times will interfere with the ability to train, tune, and complete this project.

To calculate the dimensions between layers we can look to 2d convolution documentation for a formula: https://pytorch.org/docs/stable/generated/torch.nn.Conv2d.html

In [3]:
def Conv_Out_Shape(h, w, convolution, pool = 0):
    dilation = convolution.dilation
    stride = convolution.stride
    kernel_size = convolution.kernel_size
    padding = convolution.padding
    
    hout = math.floor((h + 2 * padding[0] - dilation[0] * (kernel_size[0] - 1) - 1)/stride[0] + 1)
    wout = math.floor((w + 2 * padding[1] - dilation[1] * (kernel_size[1] - 1) - 1)/stride[1] + 1)
    
    if pool != 0:
        hout = int(hout / pool)
        wout = int(wout / pool)
    return hout, wout
In [12]:
class Cancer_Detection_CNN(nn.Module):
    
    def __init__(self, hyper_parameters):
        
        #initialize based of of Super class nn.Module
        super(Cancer_Detection_CNN, self).__init__()
        
        C, H, W = hyper_parameters["shape"]
        filters = hyper_parameters["filters"]
        linear_neurons = hyper_parameters["linear_neurons"]
        self.dropout = hyper_parameters["dropout"]
        
        #We are going to define 2 convolution layers here, calculating dimensions between
        self.first_convolution = nn.Conv2d(C, filters, kernel_size = 3)
        height, width = Conv_Out_Shape(H, W, self.first_convolution, pool = 2)
        self.second_convolution = nn.Conv2d(filters, filters, kernel_size = 3)
        height, width = Conv_Out_Shape(height, width, self.second_convolution, pool = 2)
        self.third_convolution = nn.Conv2d(filters, filters, kernel_size = 3)
        height, width = Conv_Out_Shape(height, width, self.second_convolution, pool = 2)
        self.fourth_convolution = nn.Conv2d(filters, filters, kernel_size = 3)
        height, width = Conv_Out_Shape(height, width, self.second_convolution, pool = 2)
        
        #Linear layers
        self.flat_dim = height * width * filters
        self.first_linear = nn.Linear(self.flat_dim, linear_neurons)
        self.second_linear = nn.Linear(linear_neurons, 2)
    
    #Our forward propogation will be Conv1 -> Conv2 -> Pool -> Linear1 -> Linear2 -> Output 
    def forward(self, intake):
        
        #Each convolution layer will get a relu activation function
        intake = F.relu(self.first_convolution(intake))
        
        #Pool result of convolution
        intake = F.max_pool2d(intake, 2, 2)
        
        #Second convolution
        intake = F.relu(self.second_convolution(intake))
        
        #Pool result of Convolution 
        intake = F.max_pool2d(intake, 2, 2)
        
        #Third convolution
        intake = F.relu(self.third_convolution(intake))
        
        #Pool result of Convolution 
        intake = F.max_pool2d(intake, 2, 2)
    
        #Fourt convolution
        intake = F.relu(self.fourth_convolution(intake))
        
        #Pool result of Convolution 
        intake = F.max_pool2d(intake, 2, 2)
        
        #Flatten Pool
        intake = intake.view(-1, self.flat_dim)
        
        #Linear layer 1 will get Relu while 2nd layer will get log_softmax
        intake = F.relu(self.first_linear(intake))
        
        #Apply Dropout after first dense layer
        intake = F.dropout(intake, self.dropout)
        
        #Final linear layer
        intake = self.second_linear(intake)
        
        #Output activation function
        return F.log_softmax(intake, dim = 1)

Loss function and Optimizer.¶

For loss functions I selected from the documentation: https://pytorch.org/docs/stable/nn.functional.html#loss-functions For this project I chose CrossEntropyLoss as the loss function for its ability to act as solid first choice in almost all classification settings. One of the avenues to pursue further would be identifying a loss function that may help our model achieve more accurate results. Another option that was considered but not used due to changes that would need to be effected in the Data Storage mechanism was Binary Cross Entropy Loss. In a future rendition of this project I would like to see if switching to Binary Cross Entropy produces more favorable results

For the optimizer I also selected from the documentation: https://pytorch.org/docs/stable/optim.html I selected the Adam optimizer because it takes the strengths of several other optimization methods and combines them into a single methodology. Since I lack domain knowledge and extensive experience with this dataset I don't believe I could select an optimizer better suited for this problem than Adam.

In [ ]:
#For binary classification we will start with cross entropy loss
Loss_fx = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()

#And for optimization we will use Adam, from all of the publically available notebooks for 
#this project it appears that Adam is prefered.
optimizer = Adam(First_Model.parameters(), lr = 3e-4)

Function for inputing hyperparameters and getting validation results¶

Hyperparameters we will take into account:

-epochs
-loss function
-optimiser
-learning rate
-number of filters per layer in the architecture

The following function will serve as our model training, validating, and reporting function. It will take the model architecture, the hyperparameters, and train and validate a model. The output will be histories for the training and validation loss as well as histories for the training and validation accuracy. This way we will be able to compare the performance of our models over different epochs.

In [95]:
def run_cnn(model, criterion, optimizer, train_data_loader, validate_data_loader, device, epochs):
    training_loss_history = []
    training_corrects_history = []
    val_loss_history = []
    val_corrects_history = []
    best_acc = 0.0
    min_loss = np.Inf
    
    for i in range(epochs):
        print(f"Epoch = {i + 1}/{epochs}")
        running_loss = 0.0
        running_corrects = 0.0
        val_running_loss = 0.0
        val_running_corrects = 0.0
        
        print(f"Forward Pass")
        running_total = 1
        for inputs, labels in train_data_loader:
            if running_total %100 == 0:
                print(f"Element {running_total}/{len(train_data_loader.dataset)}")
            running_total += 1
            inputs = inputs.to(device)
            labels = labels.to(device)
            
            outputs = model(inputs)
            
            loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
            
            optimizer.zero_grad()
            
            loss.backward()
            
            optimizer.step()

            _, preds = torch.max(outputs, 1)

            running_loss += loss.item()
            
            running_corrects += torch.sum(preds == labels.data)
            
        else:
            with torch.no_grad():
                for val_inputs, val_labels in validate_data_loader:
                    val_inputs = val_inputs.to(device)
                    val_labels = val_labels.to(device)
                
                    val_outputs = model(val_inputs)
                    
                    val_loss = criterion(val_outputs, val_labels)
                    
                    _, val_preds = torch.max(val_outputs, 1)
                    
                    val_running_loss += val_loss.item()
                    
                    val_running_corrects += torch.sum(val_preds == val_labels.data)

        epoch_loss = running_loss/len(train_data_loader.dataset)
        training_loss_history.append(epoch_loss)
        
        epoch_acc = running_corrects.float()/len(train_data_loader.dataset)
        training_corrects_history.append(epoch_acc)
        
        val_epoch_loss = val_running_loss/len(validate_data_loader.dataset)
        val_loss_history.append(val_epoch_loss)
        
        val_epoch_acc = val_running_corrects.float()/len(validate_data_loader.dataset)
        val_corrects_history.append(val_epoch_acc)
        
        if best_acc < val_epoch_acc:
            best_acc = val_epoch_acc
            
        if min_loss >= val_epoch_loss:
            torch.save(model.state_dict(), 'best_model.pt')
            min_loss = val_epoch_loss
        
        print(f'epoch :{i+1}')
        print(f'training loss: {round(epoch_loss, 4)}, Training accuracy {round(epoch_acc.item(), 4)}')
        print(f'validation loss: {round(val_epoch_loss,4)}, validation accuracy {round(val_epoch_acc.item(),4)} ')
        
    return model, training_loss_history, training_corrects_history, val_loss_history, val_corrects_history

This is our first instantiation of our architecture as well as implementation of our train, validate, report function.

4. Analysis of Results¶

Over 30 epochs our model was able to achieve a minimum validation loss of 0.0049 in the 21st epoch. This equated to a validation accuracy of approximately 86.27%.

In [55]:
Results = pd.DataFrame()
Results["Training_Loss"] = tlh
Results["Validation_Loss"] = vlh

Accuracy_Results = pd.DataFrame()
Accuracy_Results["Training_Accuracy"] = [x.item() for x in tch]
Accuracy_Results["Validation_Accuracy"] = [x.item() for x in bch]
In [56]:
sns.lineplot(data=Results)
Out[56]:
<AxesSubplot:>

We can see that the training loss continues to decrease as the epochs continue although at a much slower pace toward the 30th epoch. The validation loss however seems to plateau around epoch 20. Increasing the number of epochs may improve model performance slighlty, but the validation loss would suggest otherwise.

In [57]:
sns.lineplot(data=Accuracy_Results)
Out[57]:
<AxesSubplot:>

5. Alternate Architecture and Hyperparameter Tuning¶

We are going to try 3 alternate architectures, all with the hopes of increasing performance. I will limit the number of epochs to 10 each in order to keep the amount of time required to train and evaluate the models in line with project deadlines. The following are the 3 alternate architecurtes we are going to try:

  1. 4x (Convolution -> Pool) -> 1x Dense Layer -> 1x Output Layer
  2. 1x Convolution(3x3) -> Pool -> 1x Convolution(5x5) -> Pool -> 1x Convolution(3x3) -> Pool -> -> 1x Convoution(1x1) -> Pool -> 1x Dense Layer -> 1x Output Layer
  3. Same as Number 1 with Average Pool instead of Max Pool

Additionaly the transformer will have several new elements added to it for a more robust consideration of the data and how it may appear in non training scenarios.

In [29]:
data_transformer = transforms.Compose([transforms.RandomHorizontalFlip(p=0.25),
                                       transforms.RandomVerticalFlip(p=0.25),
                                       transforms.RandomRotation(45),
                                       transforms.Resize((96, 96)), 
                                       transforms.ToTensor(), 
                                       transforms.Normalize(mean=(0.5, 0.5, 0.5), std=(0.5, 0.5, 0.5))])
In [96]:
#New Architecture 1 
# 6x (Convolution -> Pool) -> 1x Dense Layer -> 1x Output Layer
# Added a padding of 1 onto each convolutional layer
# Increased Dense layer to 750 neurons
# Increased the number of filters to 8

class Cancer_Detection_CNN(nn.Module):
    
    def __init__(self, hyper_parameters):
        
        #initialize based of of Super class nn.Module
        super(Cancer_Detection_CNN, self).__init__()
        
        C, H, W = hyper_parameters["shape"]
        filters = hyper_parameters["filters"]
        linear_neurons = hyper_parameters["linear_neurons"]
        self.dropout = hyper_parameters["dropout"]
        
        #We are going to define 2 convolution layers here, calculating dimensions between
        self.first_convolution = nn.Conv2d(C, filters, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        height, width = Conv_Out_Shape(H, W, self.first_convolution, pool = 2)
        self.second_convolution = nn.Conv2d(filters, filters, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        height, width = Conv_Out_Shape(height, width, self.second_convolution, pool = 2)
        self.third_convolution = nn.Conv2d(filters, filters, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        height, width = Conv_Out_Shape(height, width, self.second_convolution, pool = 2)
        self.fourth_convolution = nn.Conv2d(filters, filters, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        height, width = Conv_Out_Shape(height, width, self.second_convolution, pool = 2)
        self.fifth_convolution = nn.Conv2d(filters, filters, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        height, width = Conv_Out_Shape(height, width, self.second_convolution, pool = 2)
        self.sixth_convolution = nn.Conv2d(filters, filters, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        height, width = Conv_Out_Shape(height, width, self.second_convolution, pool = 2)
        
        #Linear layers
        self.flat_dim = height * width * filters
        self.first_linear = nn.Linear(self.flat_dim, linear_neurons)
        self.second_linear = nn.Linear(linear_neurons, 2)
    
    #Our forward propogation will be Conv1 -> Conv2 -> Pool -> Linear1 -> Linear2 -> Output 
    def forward(self, intake):
        
        #Each convolution layer will get a relu activation function
        intake = F.relu(self.first_convolution(intake))
        
        #Pool result of convolution
        intake = F.max_pool2d(intake, 2, 2)
        
        #Second convolution
        intake = F.relu(self.second_convolution(intake))
        
        #Pool result of Convolution 
        intake = F.max_pool2d(intake, 2, 2)
        
        #Third convolution
        intake = F.relu(self.third_convolution(intake))
        
        #Pool result of Convolution 
        intake = F.max_pool2d(intake, 2, 2)
    
        #Fourth convolution
        intake = F.relu(self.fourth_convolution(intake))
        
        #Pool result of Convolution 
        intake = F.max_pool2d(intake, 2, 2)
        
        #Fifth convolution
        intake = F.relu(self.fifth_convolution(intake))
        
        #Pool result of Convolution 
        intake = F.max_pool2d(intake, 2, 2)
        
        #Sixth convolution
        intake = F.relu(self.sixth_convolution(intake))
        
        #Pool result of Convolution 
        intake = F.max_pool2d(intake, 2, 2)
        
        #Flatten Pool
        intake = intake.view(-1, self.flat_dim)
        
        #Linear layer 1 will get Relu while 2nd layer will get log_softmax
        intake = F.relu(self.first_linear(intake))
        
        #Apply Dropout after first dense layer
        intake = F.dropout(intake, self.dropout)
        
        #Final linear layer
        intake = self.second_linear(intake)
        
        #Output activation function
        return F.log_softmax(intake, dim = 1)

data = data_storage("histopathologic-cancer-detection\\train\\", data_transformer)

# New Architecture 2
# 1x Convolution(3x3) -> Pool -> 1x Convolution(5x5) -> Pool -> 1x Convolution(3x3) -> Pool -> 
# 1x Convoution(1x1) -> Pool -> 1x Dense Layer -> 1x Output Layer
# Increased dense layer to 750 Neurons
# Increased Filters to 8

class Cancer_Detection_CNN(nn.Module):
    
    def __init__(self, hyper_parameters):
        
        #initialize based of of Super class nn.Module
        super(Cancer_Detection_CNN, self).__init__()
        
        C, H, W = hyper_parameters["shape"]
        filters = hyper_parameters["filters"]
        linear_neurons = hyper_parameters["linear_neurons"]
        self.dropout = hyper_parameters["dropout"]
        
        #We are going to define 2 convolution layers here, calculating dimensions between
        self.first_convolution = nn.Conv2d(C, filters, kernel_size = 3)
        height, width = Conv_Out_Shape(H, W, self.first_convolution, pool = 2)
        self.second_convolution = nn.Conv2d(filters, filters, kernel_size = 3)
        height, width = Conv_Out_Shape(height, width, self.second_convolution, pool = 2)
        self.third_convolution = nn.Conv2d(filters, filters, kernel_size = 3)
        height, width = Conv_Out_Shape(height, width, self.second_convolution, pool = 2)
        self.fourth_convolution = nn.Conv2d(filters, filters, kernel_size = 3)
        height, width = Conv_Out_Shape(height, width, self.second_convolution, pool = 2)
        
        #Linear layers
        self.flat_dim = height * width * filters
        self.first_linear = nn.Linear(self.flat_dim, linear_neurons)
        self.second_linear = nn.Linear(linear_neurons, 2)
    
    #Our forward propogation will be Conv1 -> Conv2 -> Pool -> Linear1 -> Linear2 -> Output 
    def forward(self, intake):
        
        #Each convolution layer will get a relu activation function
        intake = F.relu(self.first_convolution(intake))
        
        #Pool result of convolution
        intake = F.max_pool2d(intake, 2, 2)
        
        #Second convolution
        intake = F.relu(self.second_convolution(intake))
        
        #Pool result of Convolution 
        intake = F.max_pool2d(intake, 2, 2)
        
        #Third convolution
        intake = F.relu(self.third_convolution(intake))
        
        #Pool result of Convolution 
        intake = F.max_pool2d(intake, 2, 2)
    
        #Fourt convolution
        intake = F.relu(self.fourth_convolution(intake))
        
        #Pool result of Convolution 
        intake = F.max_pool2d(intake, 2, 2)
        
        #Flatten Pool
        intake = intake.view(-1, self.flat_dim)
        
        #Linear layer 1 will get Relu while 2nd layer will get log_softmax
        intake = F.relu(self.first_linear(intake))
        
        #Apply Dropout after first dense layer
        intake = F.dropout(intake, self.dropout)
        
        #Final linear layer
        intake = self.second_linear(intake)
        
        #Output activation function
        return F.log_softmax(intake, dim = 1)

#New Architecture 3 
#Same as the first architecture, except with average pool replacing maxpool
# 6x (Convolution -> Pool) -> 1x Dense Layer -> 1x Output Layer
# Added a padding of 1 onto each convolutional layer
# Increased Dense layer to 750 neurons
# Increased the number of filters to 8

class Cancer_Detection_CNN(nn.Module):
    
    def __init__(self, hyper_parameters):
        
        #initialize based of of Super class nn.Module
        super(Cancer_Detection_CNN, self).__init__()
        
        C, H, W = hyper_parameters["shape"]
        filters = hyper_parameters["filters"]
        linear_neurons = hyper_parameters["linear_neurons"]
        self.dropout = hyper_parameters["dropout"]
        
        #We are going to define 2 convolution layers here, calculating dimensions between
        self.first_convolution = nn.Conv2d(C, filters, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        height, width = Conv_Out_Shape(H, W, self.first_convolution, pool = 2)
        self.second_convolution = nn.Conv2d(filters, filters, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        height, width = Conv_Out_Shape(height, width, self.second_convolution, pool = 2)
        self.third_convolution = nn.Conv2d(filters, filters, kernel_size = 3)
        height, width = Conv_Out_Shape(height, width, self.second_convolution, pool = 2)
        self.fourth_convolution = nn.Conv2d(filters, filters, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        height, width = Conv_Out_Shape(height, width, self.second_convolution, pool = 2)
        self.fifth_convolution = nn.Conv2d(filters, filters, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        height, width = Conv_Out_Shape(height, width, self.second_convolution, pool = 2)
        self.sixth_convolution = nn.Conv2d(filters, filters, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
        height, width = Conv_Out_Shape(height, width, self.second_convolution, pool = 2)
        
        #Linear layers
        self.flat_dim = height * width * filters
        self.first_linear = nn.Linear(self.flat_dim, linear_neurons)
        self.second_linear = nn.Linear(linear_neurons, 2)
    
    #Our forward propogation will be Conv1 -> Conv2 -> Pool -> Linear1 -> Linear2 -> Output 
    def forward(self, intake):
        
        #Each convolution layer will get a relu activation function
        intake = F.relu(self.first_convolution(intake))
        
        #Pool result of convolution
        intake = F.avg_pool2d(intake, 2, 2)
        
        #Second convolution
        intake = F.relu(self.second_convolution(intake))
        
        #Pool result of Convolution 
        intake = F.avg_pool2d(intake, 2, 2)
        
        #Third convolution
        intake = F.relu(self.third_convolution(intake))
        
        #Pool result of Convolution 
        intake = F.avg_pool2d(intake, 2, 2)
    
        #Fourth convolution
        intake = F.relu(self.fourth_convolution(intake))
        
        #Pool result of Convolution 
        intake = F.avg_pool2d(intake, 2, 2)
        
        #Fifth convolution
        intake = F.relu(self.fifth_convolution(intake))
        
        #Pool result of Convolution 
        intake = F.avg_pool2d(intake, 2, 2)
        
        #Sixth convolution
        intake = F.relu(self.sixth_convolution(intake))
        
        #Pool result of Convolution 
        intake = F.avg_pool2d(intake, 2, 2)
        
        #Flatten Pool
        intake = intake.view(-1, self.flat_dim)
        
        #Linear layer 1 will get Relu while 2nd layer will get log_softmax
        intake = F.relu(self.first_linear(intake))
        
        #Apply Dropout after first dense layer
        intake = F.dropout(intake, self.dropout)
        
        #Final linear layer
        intake = self.second_linear(intake)
        
        #Output activation function
        return F.log_softmax(intake, dim = 1)

import seaborn as sns
training_loss = pd.DataFrame()
training_loss["Model1_Training_Loss_History"] = alt1_tlh
training_loss["Model2_Training_Loss_History"] = alt2_tlh
training_loss["Model3_Training_Loss_History"] = alt3_tlh
sns.lineplot(data = training_loss)
Out[45]:
<AxesSubplot:>

The training loss for our models maintains a slight downwards trend towards the 10th epoch, indicating that 10 epochs may not have been enough time to achieve our optimal model performance from a training perspective. However when compared to the validation loss history it seems that we have indeed achieved our optimal performance by the 9th epoch.

validation_accuracy["Model2_Validation_Accuracy_History"] = [x.item() for x in alt2_bch]

sns.lineplot(data = validation_accuracy)
Out[53]:
<AxesSubplot:>

Finally the validation accuracy history paints a picture of two nearly identical performing models between the 1st and 3rd architecture (which makes sense since the only difference is the use of maxpool vs. avgpool respectively) with a slight edege being given to the 3rd alternative architecture with an approximate maximum validation accuracy of 89.15%.

6. Conclusion¶

While all of the models we trained for this problem seemed to come to a stable convergent condition within their alloted number of epochs some certainly outperformed others. The additional complexity introduced in the 1st and 3rd models seems to have made a significant impact on the performance and lend themselves to further research with even more complex models. Additionally adding more layers in the first dense layers output had a positive impact on all 3 alternate architectures.

Since the data presents a complex set of patterns with multiple types of variation it makes sense that the more complicated models produced better results.

Future steps with this project should focus on identifying domain specific knowledge that could be incorporated into the problem in the form of transforms or model architecture will also exploring the use of alternative loss functions (Binary Cross Entropy Loss seems like a very good contender).

In [117]:
predictions = []

#Iterate through all images in submission data
for (image, label) in sub_data:
    
    #send images and labels to gpu
    image = image.to(device)
    label = label.to(device)
    
    #have the model predict for the batch of images
    out = model_for_submission(image)
    _, preds = torch.max(out, 1)
    predicted = preds
    
    #Append each prediction
    for predict in predicted:
        predictions.append(predict.item())
